To create a dash mechanic in Unity using the Update function, you can follow the steps below.

1. Create a public float variable for the dash duration and a public float variable for the dash speed. You can adjust these values to suit your game's needs.
```
public float dashDuration = 0.5f;
public float dashSpeed = 20f;
```

2. Create a private bool variable to check if the player is dashing or not.
```
private bool isDashing = false;
```

3. In the Update function, add a check to see if the player presses a designated button to dash, and if they are not already dashing.
```
if (Input.GetKeyDown(KeyCode.Space) && !isDashing) {
    // Dash logic goes here
}
```

4. Set the isDashing variable to true and start a coroutine to handle the dash logic.
```
isDashing = true;
StartCoroutine(Dash());
```

5. In the Dash coroutine, set the player's velocity to the dash speed for the duration of the dash. You can use a timer to keep track of the duration of the dash and then set the velocity back to zero when it is over.
```
IEnumerator Dash() {
    float timer = 0f;
    while (timer < dashDuration) {
        // Set player velocity to dash speed
        playerRb.velocity = transform.forward * dashSpeed;

        timer += Time.deltaTime;
        yield return null;
    }

    // Set player velocity back to zero
    playerRb.velocity = Vector3.zero;

    // Set isDashing to false
    isDashing = false;
}
```

Note: This code assumes that you have a Rigidbody component on your player object and that your player moves forward in the direction of its transform.forward vector. If your game uses a different movement system, you will need to modify the dash logic accordingly.

If you want to create a dash mechanic in Unity without using velocity, you can follow these steps:

1. Create a public float variable for the dash distance and a public float variable for the dash duration. You can adjust these values to suit your game's needs.
```
public float dashDistance = 5f;
public float dashDuration = 0.5f;
```

2. Create a private bool variable to check if the player is dashing or not.
```
private bool isDashing = false;
```

3. In the Update function, add a check to see if the player presses a designated button to dash, and if they are not already dashing.
```
if (Input.GetKeyDown(KeyCode.Space) && !isDashing) {
    // Dash logic goes here
}
```

4. Set the isDashing variable to true and start a coroutine to handle the dash logic.
```
isDashing = true;
StartCoroutine(Dash());
```

5. In the Dash coroutine, determine the direction the player is currently facing and then move the player in that direction for the dash distance over the duration of the dash. Use a timer to keep track of the duration of the dash and stop moving the player when the timer is done.
```
IEnumerator Dash() {
    float timer = 0f;
    Vector3 startPos = transform.position;
    Vector3 endPos = transform.position + transform.forward * dashDistance;
    while (timer < dashDuration) {
        float t = timer / dashDuration;
        transform.position = Vector3.Lerp(startPos, endPos, t);

        timer += Time.deltaTime;
        yield return null;
    }

    // Set isDashing to false
    isDashing = false;
}
```

Note: This code assumes that your player moves forward in the direction of its transform.forward vector. If your game uses a different movement system, you will need to modify the dash logic accordingly.

Here's an example of complete code for a dash mechanic in Unity without using velocity:

```
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;

public class PlayerController : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float dashDistance = 5f;
    public float dashDuration = 0.5f;

    private bool isDashing = false;

    private void Update()
    {
        if (Input.GetKeyDown(KeyCode.Space) && !isDashing)
        {
            isDashing = true;
            StartCoroutine(Dash());
        }
    }

    private IEnumerator Dash()
    {
        float timer = 0f;
        Vector3 startPos = transform.position;
        Vector3 endPos = transform.position + transform.forward * dashDistance;
        while (timer < dashDuration)
        {
            float t = timer / dashDuration;
            transform.position = Vector3.Lerp(startPos, endPos, t);

            timer += Time.deltaTime;
            yield return null;
        }

        transform.position = endPos;
        isDashing = false;
    }
}
```

This code assumes that the player's transform.forward vector is the direction that they move in. When the player presses the Space key, the Dash coroutine is started. The player's position is then smoothly moved from their starting position to their end position over the duration of the dash. Once the dash is complete, the player's position is set to the end position, and the isDashing variable is set to false.

Here's an example of code that allows a player to jump with velocity in Unity:

```
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;

public class PlayerController : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float jumpForce = 10f;
    public float groundCheckDistance = 0.1f;
    public LayerMask groundMask;

    private Rigidbody playerRb;
    private bool isGrounded = false;

    private void Start()
    {
        playerRb = GetComponent<Rigidbody>();
    }

    private void Update()
    {
        if (Input.GetKeyDown(KeyCode.Space) && isGrounded)
        {
            playerRb.velocity = new Vector3(playerRb.velocity.x, jumpForce, playerRb.velocity.z);
        }
    }

    private void FixedUpdate()
    {
        isGrounded = Physics.CheckSphere(transform.position - new Vector3(0f, GetComponent<Collider>().bounds.extents.y, 0f), groundCheckDistance, groundMask);
    }
}
```

In this script, the player can jump by pressing the space key when they are grounded. When the space key is pressed, the player's velocity is set to a new Vector3 with the jump force applied to the y-axis.

To check if the player is grounded, a sphere check is performed in the FixedUpdate function. The sphere check is performed at the bottom of the player's collider to check if they are touching the ground. If the sphere check detects an object with the groundMask layer, the player is considered grounded and can jump.

